# Train a pre-trained model further with your data

- In the **'Model'** tab, select **'Use a pre-trained model'** and press **'Go'**

<img src="data:image/png;base64, "/>

![](./24.png?raw=true "Optional Title")

- Select the **'Train'** tab
- Choose an **Optimizer** (e.g. **Adam**)
- Choose a **Loss**, I would recommend jaccard_loss (IoU loss), **bce_jaccard_loss**, dice_loss or bce_dice_loss as they work well in our hands
- Choose a **Metric**, I highly recommend **IoU**

<img src="data:image/png;base64, "/>

![](./25.png?raw=true "Optional Title")

- In **'Training datasets'**, press **'+'**

<img src="data:image/png;base64, "/>

![](./26.png?raw=true "Optional Title")


- A new window pops up
- **Drag and Drop** your **train data**/folder onto the **'dataset'** field (the raw images you want to segment)
- (**Optional** if the **train data** images **comes with a black background** and a white cell outline, **mandatory otherwise**) Check 'invert'
- Select a **channel of interest** for the **input** data (i.e. any **channel containing cell outlines**)
- (Optional) If a **ROI**/crop should be used instead of the whole image to train the model, please **draw a rectangle over the region of interest**

<img src="data:image/png;base64, "/>

![](./27.png?raw=true "Optional Title")

- Select the **'output'** tab
- **Drag and Drop** your the **folder** containing **ground truth**/segmented images onto the **'dataset'** field 
- Check **'Produce EPySeg-like output'**
- **(Recommended!)** Check **'save EPySeg-style output on disk'** (this will require more disk space but will speed up the training considerably), if  little disk space is available and you have a lot of time, you can uncheck this option.
- Select a **channel of interest** for the **output** data (ideally a watershed mask or alike)

<img src="data:image/png;base64, "/>

![](./20.png?raw=true "Optional Title")

- Press **'Ok'**
- In **'Data augmentation'** press **'+'** to add **some augmentations** (of note data augmentation may impair training). I recommend **'None'** (this will train the model on raw data), **'flip'**,  **'rotate (interpolation free)'** that will rotate/flip the input data and its associated segmentation and translate. It may also be useful to add **'rotation'** (can be any angle between 0 and 360 degrees). The other augmentations are more tricky to handle and they should be used carefully.

<img src="data:image/png;base64, "/>

![](./21.png?raw=true "Optional Title")


<img src="data:image/png;base64, "/>

![](./22.png?raw=true "Optional Title")
 

- (Optional) Repeat the above steps as long with all the available train samples and corresponding ground truth/segmented images

- Simply **rely on the default parameters** for the rest of the training and press **'Go'**

<img src="data:image/png;base64, "/>

![](./23.png?raw=true "Optional Title")


- **Within hours** the model will have been **trained** on your data, the closer the IoU score is to one the best the model is likely to be, if IoU score stay close to 0, it is likely that there is something wrong with the data.
- Finally, **try predict on unseen data** (images that have not been used to train the model) to **evaluate how well the model performs** (optional: you can also compare segmentation quality to the default EPySeg model and hopefully it will be better, for several reasons it might not be the case though, it's really a trial and error process).
